{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":27,"record_hash":"sha256:4b9d96ca2ff0adc1736dee060a1770b92b9bef18536b56ad47772af8bdbe738c","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:47:32.588Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: ae3202\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 3679\nOutput:\nthey can be stored as optional record-level grouping metadata, preferably as a\nsafe provider turn key rather than a raw provider id.\n\nMinimum useful fields:\n\n- capture turn id\n- session key\n- source key\n- capture kind\n- capture timestamp\n- transcript record membership, probably by record hash and/or source record\n  index\n- optional provider turn key on transcript records, for grouping/display only\n- previous turn reference, when there is a previous capture turn in the same\n  session\n- environment snapshot\n\nThe record membership matters because `but-agentlog` already deduplicates\nrecords. Without turn membership, repeated hook capture preserves the transcript\nbut erases the boundaries between capture invocations.\n\n`TurnDetail.records` must be an ordered array. That order is authoritative for\nrendering records within a capture turn; hashes and source indexes identify the\nrecords, but they are not a replacement for sequence.\n\nThe model should distinguish:\n\n- **capture turn:** a stop-hook capture observation with new transcript records\n  and a repository environment snapshot\n- **provider turn:** a provider-native conversation grouping, such as a user\n  prompt and the resulting assistant/tool activity\n\nCapture turns are the durable agentlog concept. Provider turns are useful for UI\ngrouping when available, but they are not portable enough to define the storage\nmodel across agents.\n\nStore `previous_turn_key` as a session-wide previous capture turn pointer when\nit is available. It is not part of capture turn identity. It exists to make\ninterval evidence cheap to evaluate, for example \"worktree files seen in the\nprevious turn later appeared in commits visible in this turn.\" The first capture\nturn omits the field.\n\nImplementation should write transcript records, record hashes, the capture turn\nobject, the turn summary list entry, and derived index entries as one logical\nGitMeta update.\nIf transcript record write\n[TRUNCATED]\n have multiple unrelated applied branches at once.\n\n### Signal 2: Previous Worktree Files Becoming Committed Files\n\nFor each non-first turn, compare the previous turn's uncommitted worktree files\nagainst the current turn's observed branch commits.\n\nQuestion:\n\n> Are any files from the previous turn's uncommitted worktree file list present\n> in any commit file list in any branch observed in the current turn?\n\nIf yes, that is a strong association signal. It suggests work that was\nuncommitted at the end of one agent interaction later landed in a commit visible\nat the next capture.\n\nIf the matched commit has a change id, the association can point at that change\nid. If the matched branch has a review identifier, the association can point at\nthat review unit or pull request.\n\nIf a commit happens after one stop hook and before the next agent interaction,\nthe commit belongs to the interval between two observed capture turns. Do not\ncreate a fake empty capture turn to represent it. Store the real capture turn\nsnapshots and derive the interval evidence later.\n\nIf there is no later captured turn yet, read-time scoring may compare the latest\ncaptured worktree files against the currently queried branch, change, or PR\ncommits. Treat that as current-repo derived evidence, not as a stored historical\nobservation.\n\n### Signal 3: Direct Target Observations\n\nDirect target observations are stronger than branch counts. Examples:\n\n- a branch in the capture turn snapshot carries the queried review id or pull\n  request\n- a commit in the capture turn snapshot carries the queried change id\n- a branch in the capture turn snapshot has the queried branch name\n\nThese still are not durable ownership claims. They mean \"this target was visible\nin the repository state around this capture turn.\"\n\n### Automatic Scoring\n\nThe preferred product direction is no required human confirmation. Capture\nstores observations and lookup indexes. Read paths compute an association score\nand show related sessions automatically when confidence is high enough.\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:47:32.588Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}